{{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | width = | image1 = Statue of Uhō-dōji at Kongōshō-ji.jpg | width1 = 186 | alt1 = | caption1 = A wooden standing statue of Uhō-dōji from the Heian period, housed at [[:en:Kongōshō-ji|Kongōshō-ji]], Ise City, Mie Prefecture (Important Cultural Property of Japan) | image2 = Hokuto-shi, Senryu-ji,泉龍寺雨寶童子File.jpg | width2 = 180 | alt2 = | caption2 = Uhō-dōji suijaku painting from the Muromachi period, housed at {{ill|Senryū-ji (Hokuto City)|ja|泉龍寺 (北杜市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senryū-ji (Hokuto City)|qq=}}, Hokuto City, Yamanashi Prefecture }} '''Uhō-dōji''' (雨宝童子) is a deity in [[Ryōbu Shintō]]<ref name="Daijisen">"Uhō-dōji," [[:en:Daijisen|Daijisen]], Shogakukan</ref><ref name="Daijirin">"Uhō-dōji," [[:en:Daijirin|Daijirin]], Sanseido</ref><ref name="Nihongo Daijiten">"Uhō-dōji," [[:en:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten|Nihongo Daijiten]], Shogakukan</ref>. It is said to be the form of [[Amaterasu]] when descending to Hyūga and is also considered an incarnation of [[Vairocana]]<ref name="Daijisen"/><ref name="Daijirin"/><ref name="Nihongo Daijiten"/>.
== Characteristics == Uhō-dōji is depicted holding a {{ill|Vajra staff|ja|金剛宝棒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Vajra staff|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in the right hand and a [[:en:Cintamani|Cintamani]] in the left hand, with a [[:en:Gorintō|Gorintō]] atop the head<ref name="Daijisen"/><ref name="Daijirin"/><ref name="Nihongo Daijiten"/>.
== Cultural Properties == In [[:en:Kongōshō-ji|Kongōshō-ji]], a temple of the {{ill|Rinzai sect Nanzen-ji school|ja|臨済宗南禅寺派|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rinzai sect Nanzen-ji school|qq=}} in [[:en:Ise, Mie|Ise City]], Mie Prefecture, there is a "wooden standing statue of Uhō-dōji," designated as an [[Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]] on February 8, 1912 (Meiji 45)<ref name="Kongōshō-ji">[https://www.city.ise.mie.jp/cul_spo_edu/culture/bunkazai_shiseki/bunkazai/chokoku/1009576.html Wooden Standing Statue of Uhō-dōji], Ise City</ref>. According to temple tradition, it was carved by [[:en:Kūkai|Kūkai]] in 825 (Tenchō 2). However, the style suggests it dates to the late Heian period<ref name="Kongōshō-ji"/>.
In [[:en:Hase-dera|Hase-dera (Sakurai)]], a [[:en:Shingon-shū Buzan-ha|Shingon-shū Buzan-ha]] temple in [[:en:Sakurai, Nara|Sakurai City]], Nara Prefecture, there is another "standing statue of Uhō-dōji" to the left of the main deity, also designated as an Important Cultural Property<ref name="Hase-dera">[https://www.hasedera.or.jp/promotion/1/blog_detail.html?key=entry&value=183 Hase-dera Exhibition at Abeno Harukas Museum], Hase-dera, January 10, 2016</ref>. It is believed to have been created in 1538 (Tenbun 7) by the renowned sculptor Unshū<ref name="Hase-dera"/>.
In {{ill|Senryū-ji (Hokuto City)|ja|泉龍寺 (北杜市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Senryū-ji (Hokuto City)|qq=}}, a temple in [[:en:Hokuto, Yamanashi|Hokuto City, Yamanashi]], there is a suijaku painting of Uhō-dōji from the Muromachi period<ref>Kitamura Hiroshi, ''Takane Historical Sites Guide'', 2012, p.15</ref>. The temple's mountain name (''sangō'') is Rain Treasure Mountain (雨宝山).
